[[File:Lie In 15 -- John rehearses Give Peace A Chance.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[John Lennon]] achieved three number ones within two months of his murder in December 1980.|alt=A man with long dark hair and a beard, wearing glasses and a white jacket, playing a guitar]]
The death of a popular musician, and likewise, the use of a dead musician's work in advertising, often causes a sharp increase in sales of the musician's recordings and associated products; this has led to a number of '''posthumous number one singles in the UK''' and elsewhere.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/sales-of-amy-winehouse-records-surge-2320089.html|title=Sales of Amy Winehouse records surge|work=[[The Independent]]|date=25 July 2011|accessdate=24 August 2011|first=Rosa|last=Silverman|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2009/07/03/industry-us-jackson-sales-idUSTRE5624WF20090703|title=Michael Jackson sales surge expected to last months|publisher=[[Reuters]]|first=Ed|last=Christman|author2=Bruno, Antony |date=3 July 2009|accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/oct/26/popandrock2|work=[[The Guardian]]|title=Is that my bassline I can hear?|first=Marcus|last=Gray|date=26 October 2007|accessdate=24 August 2011|location=London}}</ref><ref name="EMCH" />  
The phenomenon, a topic of discussion in both the media and academia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eea-esem.com/files/papers/EEA-ESEM/2011/686/selling%20the%20drama_v06.pdf|title=Selling The Drama|publisher=[[University of Zurich]]|date=11 February 2011|accessdate=9 September 2011|first=Leif|last=Brandes|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923234006/http://www.eea-esem.com/files/papers/EEA-ESEM/2011/686/selling%20the%20drama_v06.pdf|archive-date=2015-09-23|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> has occurred 19 times in the UK since 1959.

The [[UK Singles Chart]] is a [[record chart]] compiled on behalf of the British record industry based on sales of [[Single (music)|single]]s in the UK. Since 1997, the chart has been compiled by [[The Official Charts Company]] and was based entirely on sales of physical singles from retail outlets until 2005, when digital downloads were included in the chart compilation.<ref name="G18">Roberts, p.14</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/3196892.stm |title=New singles formats to save the charts|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=16 October 2003 |accessdate=24 July 2011}}</ref> The UK Singles Chart originated in 1952, when ''[[NME|New Musical Express]]'' (NME) published the first chart of singles sales.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/low/entertainment/1234212.stm |title=The story of the single |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=24 July 2011| date=23 March 2001}}</ref> The positions of all songs are based on week end sale totals, from Sunday to Saturday,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/faq.php#howcompiled |title=FAQ |publisher=[[The Official UK Charts Company]] |accessdate=24 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213011104/http://theofficialcharts.com/faq.php |archivedate=13 December 2007 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> but pre-1987, the charts were released on a Tuesday due to the need for manual calculation.<ref name="G18" />

The first deceased artist to top the charts was [[Buddy Holly]], who died in [[The Day the Music Died|a plane crash on 3 February 1959]].  Three weeks later his song "[[It Doesn't Matter Anymore]]" entered the charts, and in April it reached number one.  In the 1960s [[Eddie Cochran]] and [[Jim Reeves]] achieved their first and only UK number ones after their deaths, as did [[Jimi Hendrix]] in 1970.<ref>Roberts, pp.113, 237, 417</ref>  In  August 1977 the "King of Rock'n Roll",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.scotsman.com/elvispresley/Elvis---the-King.3316164.jp|title=Elvis. . . the King of rock'n'roll who'll never lose his crown|work=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=30 August 2011|date=13 August 2007|first=Jim|last=Gilchrist|location=Edinburgh}}</ref> [[Elvis Presley]], died of a heart attack and his song "[[Way Down]]", which was already in the charts at the time, quickly climbed to number one.<ref>Roberts, p.399</ref>  Presley achieved four further posthumous number ones in the 2000s.  In 2002 his song "[[A Little Less Conversation]]", a little-known former B-side, topped the charts after being remixed by Dutch dance music producer [[Junkie XL]] for a television advertisement for [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], which broke Presley's long-standing tie with [[The Beatles]] for the most UK number ones.<ref name="EMCH">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/2048610.stm|title=Elvis makes chart history|date=16 June 2002|accessdate=25 July 2011|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>  Three years later three of his singles returned to the top spot when all his previous number one singles were re-issued to mark what would have been his 70th birthday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storyCode=11318&sectioncode=1|title=Jailhouse Rock tops UK singles chart|date=10 January 2005|work=[[Music Week]]|accessdate=25 July 2011|first=Alan|last=Jones}}</ref>

In late 1980 and early 1981 three singles by [[John Lennon]] reached number one in quick succession following [[Death of John Lennon|his murder on 8 December 1980]].  His fellow former member of The Beatles, [[George Harrison]], achieved a posthumous number one in 2002 when a re-issue of his song "[[My Sweet Lord]]", originally a number one in 1971, entered the chart at number one.  In doing so, he knocked "[[More than a Woman (Aaliyah song)|More than a Woman]]" by American singer [[Aaliyah]] from the top spot, the first time that two deceased artists had topped the charts in consecutive weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.uk.msn.com/photos/photos.aspx?ucsort=0&cp-documentid=156997342&page=3|title=George Harrison and Aaliyah's posthumous double header|first=James|last=Hurley|publisher=[[MSN Music]]|date=7 May 2011|accessdate=25 July 2011}}</ref>

==Number ones==
[[File:Elvis_Presley_promoting_Jailhouse_Rock.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Elvis Presley]] has achieved five posthumous number-one hits, one shortly after his death in 1977 and four in the 2000s with re-releases of older songs.|alt=A dark-haired young man, wearing a dark jacket and trousers and a striped top, dancing]]
[[File:George Harrison 1974 edited.jpg|thumb|right|upright|150px|In 2002 [[George Harrison]] knocked [[Aaliyah]] off the top spot, the first time that one deceased artist had replaced another at number one.]]
The following singles were all explicitly credited (either wholly or partially) to deceased artists when they reached number one on the UK Singles Chart. Singles featuring deceased artists who did not receive an explicit credit (e.g. as a member of a band), such as the 1991 re-release of [[Queen (band)|Queen]]'s "[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]" following the death of lead singer [[Freddie Mercury]], are not included.
